Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon on Monday. alphadex screening methodology Ksar Ouled Soltane doesn’t look much from the outside – a high-walled, windowless compound of tawny mud, next to a hilltop mosque. But inside is a magnificent four-storey fortified granary, with one of its two courtyards dating from the 15th century – now a Unesco site. A young guide told us that members of his tribe still use it for weekly prayers, community meetings and festivals. Each barrel-vaulted storeroom, or ghorfa, is about 8ft high and up to 30ft deep; some still have ancient palm-wood doors with hefty peg-and-hole locks. Inside, the clay and gypsum walls are decorated with handprints, family names and messages to Allah.
